p://localhost/wordpress/?p=19',5,'nav_menu_item','',0),(20,1,'2019-12-23 17:05:15','2019-12-23 17:05:15',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','20','','','2019-12-23 17:05:15','2019-12-23 17:05:15','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=20',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(21,1,'2019-12-23 17:05:16','2019-12-23 17:05:16',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','21','','','2019-12-23 17:05:16','2019-12-23 17:05:16','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=21',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(23,1,'2019-12-24 02:49:59','2019-12-24 02:49:59','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business) - </strong>The Securities and Exchange Commission is investigating BMW, the German automaker confirmed Monday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A source familiar with the investigation said the SEC is looking into the manner in which BMW reported its sales figures in the United States. The <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/sec-investigating-bmw-over-sales-practices-11577131042\" target=\"_blank\">Wall Street Journal</a> first reported this story.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BMW may have boosted its apparent sales figures by having dealers register cars that had not yet actually been sold to customers, the Journal reported.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A BMW spokesman confirmed that the company had been contacted by the SEC and was cooperating with the investigation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earlier this year, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/business/fiat-chrysler-sec-fine/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Fiat Chrysler Automobiles agreed to pay a $40 million fine</a> for its sales-reporting practices. FCA (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=FCAU&amp;source=story_quote_link\">FCAU</a>) admitted no wrongdoing in that case but, according the SEC, it had paid dealers to report \"fake sales.\" FCA also maintained a database of unreported sales, which the company could later report to maintain a facade of year-over-year monthy sales increases for over six years, the SEC claimed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BMW and Mercedes-Benz are the top two bestselling luxury brands in the United States. In 2019, excluding Mercedes\' large Sprinter and Metris vans, BMW is outselling Mercedes luxury cars and SUVs, according to data from Kelley Blue Book. The two brands are very close, though, with BMW reporting 289,080 sales as of November 2019 and Mercedes-Benz reporting 285,800, excluding the vans, according to KBB.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>-- CNN Business\' Kate Trafecante contributed to this report.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','BMW probed by SEC over sales reporting','','inherit','closed','closed','','1-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 02:49:59','2019-12-24 02:49:59','',1,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=23',0,'revision','',0),(24,1,'2019-12-24 02:50:12','2019-12-24 02:50:12','','191223171006-bmw-dealership-file-super-tease','In this Wednesday, Nov. 28, 2018, photograph, unsold 2019 3-series sedans sit at a BMW dealership in Highlands Ranch, Colo. (AP Photo/David Zalubowski)','inherit','open','closed','','191223171006-bmw-dealership-file-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 02:50:12','2019-12-24 02:50:12','',1,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191223171006-bmw-dealership-file-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(25,1,'2019-12-24 02:50:25','2019-12-24 02:50:25','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business) - </strong>The Securities and Exchange Commission is investigating BMW, the German automaker confirmed Monday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A source familiar with the investigation said the SEC is looking into the manner in which BMW reported its sales figures in the United States. The&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/sec-investigating-bmw-over-sales-practices-11577131042\" target=\"_blank\">Wall Street Journal</a>&nbsp;first reported this story.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BMW may have boosted its apparent sales figures by having dealers register cars that had not yet actually been sold to customers, the Journal reported.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A BMW spokesman confirmed that the company had been contacted by the SEC and was cooperating with the investigation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earlier this year,&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/business/fiat-chrysler-sec-fine/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Fiat Chrysler Automobiles agreed to pay a $40 million fine</a>&nbsp;for its sales-reporting practices.&nbsp;FCA&nbsp;(<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=FCAU&amp;source=story_quote_link\">FCAU</a>)&nbsp;admitted no wrongdoing in that case but, according the SEC, it had paid dealers to report \"fake sales.\" FCA also maintained a database of unreported sales, which the company could later report to maintain a facade of year-over-year monthy sales increases for over six years, the SEC claimed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BMW and Mercedes-Benz are the top two bestselling luxury brands in the United States. In 2019, excluding Mercedes\' large Sprinter and Metris vans, BMW is outselling Mercedes luxury cars and SUVs, according to data from Kelley Blue Book. The two brands are very close, though, with BMW reporting 289,080 sales as of November 2019 and Mercedes-Benz reporting 285,800, excluding the vans, according to KBB.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>-- CNN Business\' Kate Trafecante contributed to this report.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','BMW probed by SEC over sales reporting','','inherit','closed','closed','','1-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 02:50:25','2019-12-24 02:50:25','',1,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=25',0,'revision','',0),(26,1,'2019-12-24 02:55:30','2019-12-24 02:55:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business)</strong> - From the floppy disk to the headphone jack, Apple has a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://money.cnn.com/gallery/technology/2015/03/11/apple-usb-macbook/2.html\" target=\"_blank\">history</a> of removing ubiquitous technology from its gadgets before people think they\'re ready to give them up.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In some cases, Apple\'s changes have been about making devices faster, more functional, thinner, or less tied down by a tangle of wires. In other instances, Apple pushed industry standards for technology in a new direction.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, Apple (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AAPL&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AAPL</a>) could be ready to take the next big leap with <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/08/tech/apple-iphone-lightning-cable/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">a wireless iPhone</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are a few major examples of Apple ditching tech.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>A wireless iPhone?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Top Apple (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AAPL&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AAPL</a>) analyst Ming-Chi Kuo, of TF International Securities, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/08/tech/apple-iphone-lightning-cable/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">released a report </a>earlier this month predicting that Apple will remove the lightning cable port from high-end iPhone models in 2021. That would create a wireless version of the iPhone that Kuo said would help to differentiate the more expensive iPhone models and <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/30/tech/apple-earnings-third-quarter/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">boost sales</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Kuo\'s forecast isn\'t a certainty and Apple declined to comment on it. But if the predictions are borne out, it could be a sign that Apple will move toward killing the lightning charger altogether.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Apple already sells wireless charging docks that work with the iPhone 8 and later. But it\'s not clear consumers are clamoring for a fully wireless iPhone just yet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For one thing, wireless charging is just not as fast as traditional, wired charging yet. The 18-Watt wired charger was a major selling point for the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/tech/iphone-11-pro-max-review/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">iPhone 11</a> because of its rapid charging speed, according to Wedbush Securities analyst Dan Ives. By contrast, the fastest wireless chargers offer only 7.5 watts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There would be other challenges, too. Customers would have to toss their wired headphones and chargers and buy new ones. And many older cars enabled with CarPlay — Apple\'s technology that lets users see Apple Maps, Music and other apps on their car screens — require a plug for the feature to work.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>Death of the disk drive</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the 1998 release of the iMac, Apple did away with the floppy disk drive, leaving only a rewritable CD drive.That lasted about 10 years, and then Apple killed the CD drive, as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>The MagSafe charger</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This popular charging technology disappeared from Apple laptops with the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://money.cnn.com/2016/04/19/technology/apple-macbook/\" target=\"_blank\">2015 MacBook Air</a> and 2016 MacBook Pro. It was a controversial decision — the magnetic charging cable was popular because if it was unexpectedly yanked on (say, by tripping over the cord), the charger would easily disconnect rather than pulling the laptop down to the ground.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":27,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191219154830-20191219-apple-60w-magsafe-power-adapter-medium-plus-169.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-27\"/><figcaption>The MagSafe cable used a magnetic connection to charge laptops, rather than plugging into a traditional port.</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>hose Macs also did away with the traditional USB port. The USB port and MagSafe charger were replaced with a USB-C port that doubles as a charger and a way to quickly transfer data to and from the computer.The switch allowed Apple to make a thinner, lighter computer but it meant that users who still used the larger USB drives had to buy adapters to connect them to their new computers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>The 30-pin charging cable</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2012, Apple switched to the lightning cable, and Apple customers said goodbye to the larger 30-pin charging port, which had been used in iPhones, iPads and iPods for a decade.But the company has slowly been phasing the lightning cable out of its iPad designs. And the lightning cable doesn\'t plug into most Apple computers these days.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Why Apple killed the floppy disk and headphone jack before you were ready to give them up','','publish','open','open','','why-apple-killed-the-floppy-disk-and-headphone-jack-before-you-were-ready-to-give-them-up','','','2019-12-24 02:55:30','2019-12-24 02:55:30','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=26',0,'post','',0),(27,1,'2019-12-24 02:53:47','2019-12-24 02:53:47','','191219154830-20191219-apple-60w-magsafe-power-adapter-medium-plus-169','','inherit','open','closed','','191219154830-20191219-apple-60w-magsafe-power-adapter-medium-plus-169','','','2019-12-24 02:53:47','2019-12-24 02:53:47','',26,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191219154830-20191219-apple-60w-magsafe-power-adapter-medium-plus-169.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(28,1,'2019-12-24 02:55:27','2019-12-24 02:55:27','','191216082635-apple-devices-charging-file-super-tease','An AirPower mat is seen charging multiple devices during a media event at Apple\'s new headquarters in Cupertino, California on September 12, 2017.  / AFP PHOTO / Josh Edelson        (Photo credit should read JOSH EDELSON/AFP via Getty Images)','inherit','open','closed','','191216082635-apple-devices-charging-file-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 02:55:27','2019-12-24 02:55:27','',26,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191216082635-apple-devices-charging-file-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(29,1,'2019-12-24 02:55:30','2019-12-24 02:55:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business)</strong> - From the floppy disk to the headphone jack, Apple has a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://money.cnn.com/gallery/technology/2015/03/11/apple-usb-macbook/2.html\" target=\"_blank\">history</a> of removing ubiquitous technology from its gadgets before people think they\'re ready to give them up.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In some cases, Apple\'s changes have been about making devices faster, more functional, thinner, or less tied down by a tangle of wires. In other instances, Apple pushed industry standards for technology in a new direction.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, Apple (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AAPL&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AAPL</a>) could be ready to take the next big leap with <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/08/tech/apple-iphone-lightning-cable/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">a wireless iPhone</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are a few major examples of Apple ditching tech.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>A wireless iPhone?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Top Apple (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AAPL&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AAPL</a>) analyst Ming-Chi Kuo, of TF International Securities, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/08/tech/apple-iphone-lightning-cable/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">released a report </a>earlier this month predicting that Apple will remove the lightning cable port from high-end iPhone models in 2021. That would create a wireless version of the iPhone that Kuo said would help to differentiate the more expensive iPhone models and <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/30/tech/apple-earnings-third-quarter/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">boost sales</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Kuo\'s forecast isn\'t a certainty and Apple declined to comment on it. But if the predictions are borne out, it could be a sign that Apple will move toward killing the lightning charger altogether.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Apple already sells wireless charging docks that work with the iPhone 8 and later. But it\'s not clear consumers are clamoring for a fully wireless iPhone just yet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For one thing, wireless charging is just not as fast as traditional, wired charging yet. The 18-Watt wired charger was a major selling point for the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/tech/iphone-11-pro-max-review/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">iPhone 11</a> because of its rapid charging speed, according to Wedbush Securities analyst Dan Ives. By contrast, the fastest wireless chargers offer only 7.5 watts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There would be other challenges, too. Customers would have to toss their wired headphones and chargers and buy new ones. And many older cars enabled with CarPlay — Apple\'s technology that lets users see Apple Maps, Music and other apps on their car screens — require a plug for the feature to work.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>Death of the disk drive</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the 1998 release of the iMac, Apple did away with the floppy disk drive, leaving only a rewritable CD drive.That lasted about 10 years, and then Apple killed the CD drive, as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>The MagSafe charger</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This popular charging technology disappeared from Apple laptops with the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://money.cnn.com/2016/04/19/technology/apple-macbook/\" target=\"_blank\">2015 MacBook Air</a> and 2016 MacBook Pro. It was a controversial decision — the magnetic charging cable was popular because if it was unexpectedly yanked on (say, by tripping over the cord), the charger would easily disconnect rather than pulling the laptop down to the ground.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":27,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191219154830-20191219-apple-60w-magsafe-power-adapter-medium-plus-169.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-27\"/><figcaption>The MagSafe cable used a magnetic connection to charge laptops, rather than plugging into a traditional port.</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>hose Macs also did away with the traditional USB port. The USB port and MagSafe charger were replaced with a USB-C port that doubles as a charger and a way to quickly transfer data to and from the computer.The switch allowed Apple to make a thinner, lighter computer but it meant that users who still used the larger USB drives had to buy adapters to connect them to their new computers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>The 30-pin charging cable</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2012, Apple switched to the lightning cable, and Apple customers said goodbye to the larger 30-pin charging port, which had been used in iPhones, iPads and iPods for a decade.But the company has slowly been phasing the lightning cable out of its iPad designs. And the lightning cable doesn\'t plug into most Apple computers these days.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Why Apple killed the floppy disk and headphone jack before you were ready to give them up','','inherit','closed','closed','','26-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 02:55:30','2019-12-24 02:55:30','',26,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=29',0,'revision','',0),(30,1,'2019-12-24 02:57:22','2019-12-24 02:57:22','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business) - </strong>Boeing CEO Dennis Muilenburg was ousted on Monday after a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/19/business/boeing-credit-ratings-cut/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">tumultuous</a> period in which the company faced a series of setbacks, including two fatal crashes, delays and numerous issues with its 737 Max airplane. Boeing continues to struggle to get its most important product back in the air.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chairman David Calhoun will take over as CEO, effective January 13, 2020.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=BA&amp;source=story_quote_link\">BA</a>) said in a press release that its board of directors decided to part ways with Muilenberg in part because its customers and regulators no longer trusted the company\'s decision-making.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"A change in leadership was necessary to restore confidence in the company moving forward as it works to repair relationships with regulators, customers, and all other stakeholders,\" the company said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing\'s 737 Max, which was the company\'s bestselling commercial jet, was <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/03/13/politics/donald-trump-boeing-faa/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">grounded</a> worldwide in March 2019 after two fatal crashes killed 346 people. It still hasn\'t returned to flight, despite Boeing\'s efforts to clear a software fix with regulators.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The company said earlier this month that it would suspend<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/16/business/boeing-stock-737-max-curb-production/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"> production</a> of the 737 Max starting in January. Boeing has continued to produce the 737 Max during its grounding, but uncertainty about when the federal regulators will clear the planes for flight has made production untenable. Boeing shifted its timeline for the 737 Max\'s return to the skies several times throughout the year, as it became evident that it could not easily satisfy regulators\' concerns about the plane\'s safety.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing also lost lawmakers\' confidence, particularly after a former employee testified before Congress earlier this month that <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/11/politics/fatally-flawed-737-max-had-significantly-higher-crash-risk-faa-concluded/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Boeing ignored safety concerns</a> when building the 737 Max. One whistleblower suggested Boeing had a culture problem in which it cut corners to save on costs and made production mistakes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other problems have plagued Boeing during Muilenberg\'s tenure. Another version of the 737 Max, an older version of <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/10/business/boeing-737-ng-grounding/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">737 NG aircraft</a>, was found to have structural cracks that forced airlines to inspect their fleets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/22/tech/boeing-starliner-landing-deorbit-scn/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">spacecraft</a> the company is building to ferry NASA astronauts to the International Space Station malfunctioned last week during its first-ever trip to space. The uncrewed test flight, which came after years of delays and setbacks, was intended to be the final major test before it was finally ready to fly humans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Boeing CEO Dennis Muilenburg ousted after a disastrous year','','publish','open','open','','boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-ousted-after-a-disastrous-year','','','2019-12-24 02:57:22','2019-12-24 02:57:22','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=30',0,'post','',0),(31,1,'2019-12-24 02:57:17','2019-12-24 02:57:17','','191105081843-01-boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-1029-super-tease','Boeing CEO Dennis Muilenburg testifies at a hearing in front of congressional lawmakers on Capitol Hill in Washington, DC on October 30, 2019. (Photo by Olivier Douliery / AFP) (Photo by OLIVIER DOULIERY/AFP via Getty Images)','inherit','open','closed','','191105081843-01-boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-1029-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 02:57:17','2019-12-24 02:57:17','',30,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191105081843-01-boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-1029-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(32,1,'2019-12-24 02:57:22','2019-12-24 02:57:22','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business) - </strong>Boeing CEO Dennis Muilenburg was ousted on Monday after a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/19/business/boeing-credit-ratings-cut/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">tumultuous</a> period in which the company faced a series of setbacks, including two fatal crashes, delays and numerous issues with its 737 Max airplane. Boeing continues to struggle to get its most important product back in the air.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chairman David Calhoun will take over as CEO, effective January 13, 2020.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=BA&amp;source=story_quote_link\">BA</a>) said in a press release that its board of directors decided to part ways with Muilenberg in part because its customers and regulators no longer trusted the company\'s decision-making.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"A change in leadership was necessary to restore confidence in the company moving forward as it works to repair relationships with regulators, customers, and all other stakeholders,\" the company said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing\'s 737 Max, which was the company\'s bestselling commercial jet, was <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/03/13/politics/donald-trump-boeing-faa/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">grounded</a> worldwide in March 2019 after two fatal crashes killed 346 people. It still hasn\'t returned to flight, despite Boeing\'s efforts to clear a software fix with regulators.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The company said earlier this month that it would suspend<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/16/business/boeing-stock-737-max-curb-production/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"> production</a> of the 737 Max starting in January. Boeing has continued to produce the 737 Max during its grounding, but uncertainty about when the federal regulators will clear the planes for flight has made production untenable. Boeing shifted its timeline for the 737 Max\'s return to the skies several times throughout the year, as it became evident that it could not easily satisfy regulators\' concerns about the plane\'s safety.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing also lost lawmakers\' confidence, particularly after a former employee testified before Congress earlier this month that <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/11/politics/fatally-flawed-737-max-had-significantly-higher-crash-risk-faa-concluded/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Boeing ignored safety concerns</a> when building the 737 Max. One whistleblower suggested Boeing had a culture problem in which it cut corners to save on costs and made production mistakes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other problems have plagued Boeing during Muilenberg\'s tenure. Another version of the 737 Max, an older version of <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/10/business/boeing-737-ng-grounding/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">737 NG aircraft</a>, was found to have structural cracks that forced airlines to inspect their fleets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/22/tech/boeing-starliner-landing-deorbit-scn/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">spacecraft</a> the company is building to ferry NASA astronauts to the International Space Station malfunctioned last week during its first-ever trip to space. The uncrewed test flight, which came after years of delays and setbacks, was intended to be the final major test before it was finally ready to fly humans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Boeing CEO Dennis Muilenburg ousted after a disastrous year','','inherit','closed','closed','','30-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 02:57:22','2019-12-24 02:57:22','',30,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=32',0,'revision','',0),(33,1,'2019-12-24 03:04:15','2019-12-24 03:04:15','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Hong Kong (CNN Business) - </strong>A Chinese printing company has denied allegations that it forced prisoners to pack Christmas cards that were sold by British retailer Tesco (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=TSCDF&amp;source=story_quote_link\">TSCDF</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The claims first came to light when<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tesco-charity-cards-packed-by-chinas-prison-slaves-v9psp9fqx\" target=\"_blank\">The Sunday Times</a> reported that six-year-old Florence Widdicombe, who lives in south London, opened a box of Tesco charity Christmas cards and discovered a desperate message inside one of them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We are foreign prisoners in Shanghai Qingpu prison China,\" the message read. \"Forced to work against our will. Please help us and notify [a] human rights organization.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tesco responded swiftly, saying in a statement Sunday that it had suspended production at a Chinese factory following the allegations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On Monday, Zhejiang Yunguang Printing, a Chinese firm that supplies greeting cards to Tesco, pushed back strongly against any suggestion that it used forced labor, saying it was \"investigating whether those cards were printed by us.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We have never been involved in such activities that the media reported,\" a representative for the company said when reached by CNN by phone. \"We think someone is smearing us. The only thing I can tell you is that we don\'t have labor from Shanghai Qingpu prison, so you should ask Qingpu prison what\'s exactly going on and why their workers would write such notes.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The representative declined to share his or her name or position with the company.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The card had urged the recipient to \"contact Mr Peter Humphrey\" — a former British journalist who spent two years in Chinese prisons, including Qingpu. Widdicombe\'s father contacted Humphrey, who reported the story for The Sunday Times.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Humphrey wrote that he contacted several members of an \"informal network of ex-prisoners,\" who told him that inmates in the foreign prisoners unit are being forced into \"mundane manual assembly or packaging tasks.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another ex-prisoner who now lives in the United Kingdom told Humphrey that prisoners had been packaging Christmas cards and gift tags for Tesco for at least two years. Humphrey himself, who said he was jailed on \"bogus charges\" for his work as a corporate fraud investigator, said that during his time in Qingpu prison he had seen \"product tags with the names of other high street brands.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chinese officials also addressed the newspaper report. On Monday, Geng Shuang, a spokesperson at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, accused Humphrey of fabricating the article, and said no foreigner has been put into forced labor at that particular prison.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"When I saw [the message], I immediately knew it was absolutely genuine and fitted with everything I knew about the prison and the labor there,\" he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CNN has also contacted The Sunday Times and the Shanghai Prison Administration, which oversees the Qingpu prison, for comment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>— CNN\'s Amy Woodyatt,</em> <em>David Culver, Duarte Mendonca and Rosanne Roobeek contributed to this report.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Tesco\'s Chinese Christmas card maker denies using forced prison labor','','publish','open','open','','tescos-chinese-christmas-card-maker-denies-using-forced-prison-labor','','','2019-12-24 03:04:15','2019-12-24 03:04:15','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=33',0,'post','',0),(34,1,'2019-12-24 03:04:11','2019-12-24 03:04:11','','191223090218-02-tesco-file-super-tease','GLASGOW, SCOTLAND - OCTOBER 23:  A general view of a Tesco supermarket on October 23, 2014 in Glasgow, Scotland.Tesco one of Britains biggest supermarkets has announced a 91.9% plunge in pre-tax profits to ??112 million for the first half of the year.  (Photo by Jeff J Mitchell/Getty Images)','inherit','open','closed','','191223090218-02-tesco-file-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 03:04:11','2019-12-24 03:04:11','',33,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191223090218-02-tesco-file-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(35,1,'2019-12-24 03:04:15','2019-12-24 03:04:15','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Hong Kong (CNN Business) - </strong>A Chinese printing company has denied allegations that it forced prisoners to pack Christmas cards that were sold by British retailer Tesco (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=TSCDF&amp;source=story_quote_link\">TSCDF</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The claims first came to light when<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tesco-charity-cards-packed-by-chinas-prison-slaves-v9psp9fqx\" target=\"_blank\">The Sunday Times</a> reported that six-year-old Florence Widdicombe, who lives in south London, opened a box of Tesco charity Christmas cards and discovered a desperate message inside one of them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We are foreign prisoners in Shanghai Qingpu prison China,\" the message read. \"Forced to work against our will. Please help us and notify [a] human rights organization.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tesco responded swiftly, saying in a statement Sunday that it had suspended production at a Chinese factory following the allegations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On Monday, Zhejiang Yunguang Printing, a Chinese firm that supplies greeting cards to Tesco, pushed back strongly against any suggestion that it used forced labor, saying it was \"investigating whether those cards were printed by us.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"We have never been involved in such activities that the media reported,\" a representative for the company said when reached by CNN by phone. \"We think someone is smearing us. The only thing I can tell you is that we don\'t have labor from Shanghai Qingpu prison, so you should ask Qingpu prison what\'s exactly going on and why their workers would write such notes.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The representative declined to share his or her name or position with the company.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The card had urged the recipient to \"contact Mr Peter Humphrey\" — a former British journalist who spent two years in Chinese prisons, including Qingpu. Widdicombe\'s father contacted Humphrey, who reported the story for The Sunday Times.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Humphrey wrote that he contacted several members of an \"informal network of ex-prisoners,\" who told him that inmates in the foreign prisoners unit are being forced into \"mundane manual assembly or packaging tasks.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another ex-prisoner who now lives in the United Kingdom told Humphrey that prisoners had been packaging Christmas cards and gift tags for Tesco for at least two years. Humphrey himself, who said he was jailed on \"bogus charges\" for his work as a corporate fraud investigator, said that during his time in Qingpu prison he had seen \"product tags with the names of other high street brands.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chinese officials also addressed the newspaper report. On Monday, Geng Shuang, a spokesperson at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, accused Humphrey of fabricating the article, and said no foreigner has been put into forced labor at that particular prison.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"When I saw [the message], I immediately knew it was absolutely genuine and fitted with everything I knew about the prison and the labor there,\" he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CNN has also contacted The Sunday Times and the Shanghai Prison Administration, which oversees the Qingpu prison, for comment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>— CNN\'s Amy Woodyatt,</em> <em>David Culver, Duarte Mendonca and Rosanne Roobeek contributed to this report.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Tesco\'s Chinese Christmas card maker denies using forced prison labor','','inherit','closed','closed','','33-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 03:04:15','2019-12-24 03:04:15','',33,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=35',0,'revision','',0),(36,1,'2019-12-24 03:06:00','2019-12-24 03:06:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Hong Kong (CNN Business) - </strong>China will reduce import tariffs on hundreds of goods next week as it tries to boost trade, shore up its <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/17/economy/china-gdp-economy-trade-war/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">slowing economy</a> and soften the impact of a devastating swine fever epidemic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Chinese government <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.gov.cn/xinwen/2019-12/23/5463213/files/5c649184324940cdb39f3cba2d662193.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">announced</a> Monday that it would lower import duties on frozen pork, semiconductor parts and more than 800 other items ranging from consumer goods to high-tech products. The rollbacks begin January 1.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China\'s economy has taken hits from all sides this year. Domestic demand has slowed, debt levels are mounting and the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/22/business/china-us-trade-cold-war/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">prolonged trade war</a> with the United States continues to take its toll.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The skyrocketing <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/28/business/china-african-swine-fever-pork/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">price of pork</a> — a staple of the Chinese diet — may also explain why China is easing frozen pork tariffs from 12% to 8%. <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/02/01/china/china-african-swine-flu-in-year-of-the-pig-intl/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">African swine fever</a> has ravaged the country\'s pig farms, causing the cost of the meat to more than double last month compared to a year earlier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earlier this month, the spike in pork prices caused China\'s consumer inflation to rise by the quickest pace in nearly eight years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Chinese government on Monday said that the pork tariff reductions were needed to \"better meet people\'s daily needs.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China is looking at measures beyond tariff cuts as it tries to avert a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/20/economy/china-economy-rate-cut-pboc/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">sharp economic slowdown</a>. Monday\'s announcement came one day after Beijing announced 28 new measures to step up support for the country\'s struggling private sector, including bigger tax cuts and easier access to bank loans. The private sector is crucial to China\'s growth, but itscompanies face more funding difficulties than their state-owned peers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China\'s trade relationships with other countries are also a consideration. The country is still expected soon to sign a \"phase one\" trade deal with the United States, which is expected to include Chinese purchases of American farm products.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One analyst considered Monday\'s announcement an \"encouraging olive branch\" as that deal moves closer toward reality. Stephen Innes, chief Asia market strategy as AxiTrader, said Beijing might be showing Washington that it wants to keep opening up its market and economy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"It suggests that harmonious discussions continue\" as the two sides wrap up \"phase one\" and head into \"phase two\" of trade negotiations, Innes added.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China\'s move also suggests that the country is trying to encourage trade with other countries as it hashes out its dispute with the United States, said Alex Capri, senior fellow and lecturer at the National University of Singapore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Capri said Beijing likely wants to increase ties in the semiconductor sector with countries like South Korea and Japan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','China cuts some tariffs to boost trade and take heat out of pork prices','','publish','open','open','','china-cuts-some-tariffs-to-boost-trade-and-take-heat-out-of-pork-prices','','','2019-12-24 03:06:00','2019-12-24 03:06:00','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=36',0,'post','',0),(37,1,'2019-12-24 03:05:57','2019-12-24 03:05:57','','191223003057-china-cuts-tariffs-pork-super-tease','This photo taken on December 19, 2019 shows people trying to buy meat at a newly-opened supermarket in Binzhou, in China\'s eastern Shandong Province. - The supermarket offered 3 tonnes of pork at discounted prices as a promotion. Pork prices in China have doubled this year following an outbreak of African swine fever. (Photo by STR / AFP) / China OUT (Photo by STR/AFP via Getty Images)','inherit','open','closed','','191223003057-china-cuts-tariffs-pork-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 03:05:57','2019-12-24 03:05:57','',36,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191223003057-china-cuts-tariffs-pork-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(38,1,'2019-12-24 03:06:00','2019-12-24 03:06:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Hong Kong (CNN Business) - </strong>China will reduce import tariffs on hundreds of goods next week as it tries to boost trade, shore up its <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/17/economy/china-gdp-economy-trade-war/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">slowing economy</a> and soften the impact of a devastating swine fever epidemic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Chinese government <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.gov.cn/xinwen/2019-12/23/5463213/files/5c649184324940cdb39f3cba2d662193.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">announced</a> Monday that it would lower import duties on frozen pork, semiconductor parts and more than 800 other items ranging from consumer goods to high-tech products. The rollbacks begin January 1.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China\'s economy has taken hits from all sides this year. Domestic demand has slowed, debt levels are mounting and the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/22/business/china-us-trade-cold-war/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">prolonged trade war</a> with the United States continues to take its toll.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The skyrocketing <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/28/business/china-african-swine-fever-pork/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">price of pork</a> — a staple of the Chinese diet — may also explain why China is easing frozen pork tariffs from 12% to 8%. <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/02/01/china/china-african-swine-flu-in-year-of-the-pig-intl/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">African swine fever</a> has ravaged the country\'s pig farms, causing the cost of the meat to more than double last month compared to a year earlier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Earlier this month, the spike in pork prices caused China\'s consumer inflation to rise by the quickest pace in nearly eight years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Chinese government on Monday said that the pork tariff reductions were needed to \"better meet people\'s daily needs.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China is looking at measures beyond tariff cuts as it tries to avert a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/20/economy/china-economy-rate-cut-pboc/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">sharp economic slowdown</a>. Monday\'s announcement came one day after Beijing announced 28 new measures to step up support for the country\'s struggling private sector, including bigger tax cuts and easier access to bank loans. The private sector is crucial to China\'s growth, but itscompanies face more funding difficulties than their state-owned peers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China\'s trade relationships with other countries are also a consideration. The country is still expected soon to sign a \"phase one\" trade deal with the United States, which is expected to include Chinese purchases of American farm products.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One analyst considered Monday\'s announcement an \"encouraging olive branch\" as that deal moves closer toward reality. Stephen Innes, chief Asia market strategy as AxiTrader, said Beijing might be showing Washington that it wants to keep opening up its market and economy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"It suggests that harmonious discussions continue\" as the two sides wrap up \"phase one\" and head into \"phase two\" of trade negotiations, Innes added.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>China\'s move also suggests that the country is trying to encourage trade with other countries as it hashes out its dispute with the United States, said Alex Capri, senior fellow and lecturer at the National University of Singapore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Capri said Beijing likely wants to increase ties in the semiconductor sector with countries like South Korea and Japan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','China cuts some tariffs to boost trade and take heat out of pork prices','','inherit','closed','closed','','36-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 03:06:00','2019-12-24 03:06:00','',36,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=38',0,'revision','',0),(39,1,'2019-12-24 03:07:32','2019-12-24 03:07:32','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>San Francisco (CNN Business) - </strong>Rivian, the company making electric vehicles for Amazon and Ford, just got a big influx of cash.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Michigan-based carmaker has <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://media.rivian.com/rivian-announces-1-3-billion-funding-round-led-by-t-rowe-price/\" target=\"_blank\">raised $1.3 billion</a> in a new funding round led by investment firm and Tesla (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=TSLA&amp;source=story_quote_link\">TSLA</a>) shareholder T. Rowe Price, Rivian announced Monday. Amazon (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AMZN&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AMZN</a>) and Ford (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=F&amp;source=story_quote_link\">F</a>) also took part in the funding round, the company said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The latest investment is Rivian\'s fourth of 2019 and brings its fundraising for the year to nearly $3 billion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"This investment demonstrates confidence in our team, products, technology and strategy -- we are extremely excited to have the support from such strong shareholders,\" Rivian founder and CEO RJ Scaringe said in a statement.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Aside from developing its own vehicles — the R1T pickup truck and the R1S SUV — the company is also <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/24/investing/ford-rivian/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">helping Ford develop a new plug-in battery vehicle</a> and is <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/19/tech/amazon-climate-pledge/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">making 100,000 electric delivery vans</a> for Amazon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seen as the biggest competitor to <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/22/cars/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-truck/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Tesla\'s new Cybertruck</a>, Rivian claims its electric pickup can travel more than 400 miles on a single charge, carry nearly 1,800 pounds of payload and can tow another 11,000 pounds. The most expensive version of the Cybertruck can carry 3,500 pounds and tow 14,000 pounds, while traveling 500 miles on a single charge. The base model will have a range of 250 miles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ford, meanwhile, is also developing an electric version of its own classic pickup, the F-150, which it says it expects to roll out \"<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/26/cars/ford-tesla-cybertruck-challenge/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">in a few years</a>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The company has started taking pre-orders for both its launch vehicles, which have a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/06/success/rivian-electric-pickup/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">starting price of $69,000</a>. Rivian will manufacture the pickup and SUV at a former Mitsubishi factory in Normal, Illinois, and plans to start delivering them to customers towards the end of next year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Electric pickup truck company Rivian raises $1.3 billion','','publish','open','open','','electric-pickup-truck-company-rivian-raises-1-3-billion','','','2019-12-24 03:07:32','2019-12-24 03:07:32','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=39',0,'post','',0),(40,1,'2019-12-24 03:07:28','2019-12-24 03:07:28','','191223135203-02-rivian-truck-super-tease','','inherit','open','closed','','191223135203-02-rivian-truck-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 03:07:28','2019-12-24 03:07:28','',39,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191223135203-02-rivian-truck-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(41,1,'2019-12-24 03:07:32','2019-12-24 03:07:32','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>San Francisco (CNN Business) - </strong>Rivian, the company making electric vehicles for Amazon and Ford, just got a big influx of cash.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Michigan-based carmaker has <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://media.rivian.com/rivian-announces-1-3-billion-funding-round-led-by-t-rowe-price/\" target=\"_blank\">raised $1.3 billion</a> in a new funding round led by investment firm and Tesla (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=TSLA&amp;source=story_quote_link\">TSLA</a>) shareholder T. Rowe Price, Rivian announced Monday. Amazon (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AMZN&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AMZN</a>) and Ford (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=F&amp;source=story_quote_link\">F</a>) also took part in the funding round, the company said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The latest investment is Rivian\'s fourth of 2019 and brings its fundraising for the year to nearly $3 billion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"This investment demonstrates confidence in our team, products, technology and strategy -- we are extremely excited to have the support from such strong shareholders,\" Rivian founder and CEO RJ Scaringe said in a statement.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Aside from developing its own vehicles — the R1T pickup truck and the R1S SUV — the company is also <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/24/investing/ford-rivian/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">helping Ford develop a new plug-in battery vehicle</a> and is <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/19/tech/amazon-climate-pledge/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">making 100,000 electric delivery vans</a> for Amazon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seen as the biggest competitor to <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/22/cars/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-truck/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Tesla\'s new Cybertruck</a>, Rivian claims its electric pickup can travel more than 400 miles on a single charge, carry nearly 1,800 pounds of payload and can tow another 11,000 pounds. The most expensive version of the Cybertruck can carry 3,500 pounds and tow 14,000 pounds, while traveling 500 miles on a single charge. The base model will have a range of 250 miles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ford, meanwhile, is also developing an electric version of its own classic pickup, the F-150, which it says it expects to roll out \"<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/26/cars/ford-tesla-cybertruck-challenge/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">in a few years</a>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The company has started taking pre-orders for both its launch vehicles, which have a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/06/success/rivian-electric-pickup/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">starting price of $69,000</a>. Rivian will manufacture the pickup and SUV at a former Mitsubishi factory in Normal, Illinois, and plans to start delivering them to customers towards the end of next year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Electric pickup truck company Rivian raises $1.3 billion','','inherit','closed','closed','','39-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 03:07:32','2019-12-24 03:07:32','',39,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=41',0,'revision','',0),(42,1,'2019-12-24 03:10:25','2019-12-24 03:10:25','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business) - </strong>The listing on Amazon (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AMZN&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AMZN</a>) described it as a \"4 in 1 Baby car seat and Stroller\" and featured images of a popular brand called Doona, including a photo of the US President\'s daughter, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.pinterest.com/pin/449585975299565156/\" target=\"_blank\">Ivanka Trump, with hers</a>. Listed for $299, this copycat  was $200 cheaper than a real Doona. It was also potentially dangerous for children. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The car seat broke into pieces in a  30 mph crash test commissioned by CNN, failing to meet the basic standards set by US regulators. Video of the test shows the toddler dummy twisting as the car seat fractures and slides forward, with plastic pieces that have broken off it flying through the air. In an identical crash test scenario, an authentic Doona met federal requirements, with the car seat remaining in one piece and in place around the dummy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://thecarseatlady.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Dr. Alisa Baer</a>, a pediatrician and nationally certified child passenger safety instructor, reviewed the test results and said in a real crash such a car seat failure could put a child in \"grave danger,\" and lead to injuries to a child\'s chest, neck or head, including a traumatic brain injury. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CNN bought the copycat Doona and had it crash-tested at the University of Michigan Transportation Research Institute as part of a months-long investigation into the sale of counterfeit and patent-infringing children\'s products on Amazon. Seven different business owners told CNN their products were being actively targeted by counterfeiters using Amazon\'s marketplace for third-party vendors. The businesses said Amazon put the onus on them to report suspicious listings and that this often amounted to a game of \"whack-a-mole,\" in which new listings appeared almost as soon as flagged ones were taken down.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":43,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191219171403-03-copycat-doona-crash-test-super-169.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-43\"/><figcaption>A car seat purchased on Amazon fractured in a 30 mph crash test, failing to meet federal standards</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Under current US case law, Amazon is not liable when third-party products sold on its site directly infringe on intellectual property or have safety defects. The liability lies with the third-party seller. This is fundamentally different from how the law treats brick-and-mortar retailers like Target (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=TGT&amp;source=story_quote_link\">TGT</a>) or Walmart (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=WMT&amp;source=story_quote_link\">WMT</a>) or even your corner grocery. If you find a product at a physical store that infringes on your trademark, or you buy something defective there, you can sue the store even though they didn\'t make the product. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Counterfeits are a problem for many ecommerce platforms, not just Amazon, but Amazon is the world\'s largest ecommerce platform and its dominance is growing. According to <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.emarketer.com/content/us-ecommerce-2019\" target=\"_blank\">an estimate from data firm eMarketer</a>, Amazon controls 37.7% of US ecommerce sales and that share is expected to grow. Many of the brands that spoke to CNN told us they can\'t afford not to sell their products on Amazon. As an Amazon spokesperson said to CNN in a statement, \"our customers expect that when they make a purchase through Amazon\'s store—either directly from Amazon or from one of its millions of third-party sellers—they will receive authentic products.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amiad Raviv, the commercial manager of Doona, said the company has found more than 40 Amazon listings this year that contained fake versions of its products or versions that infringed on its intellectual property. Doona flags the listings they are concerned about to Amazon, which then removes them. According to Raviv and the other business owners CNN spoke with, this piecemeal process means listings are often online for several days, leading to a significant window when consumers can buy the potentially dangerous product. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The imitation Doonas are sold through Amazon\'s website or app, but not by Amazon directly. According to <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://ir.aboutamazon.com/static-files/0f9e36b1-7e1e-4b52-be17-145dc9d8b5ec\" target=\"_blank\">Amazon\'s 2018 annual report</a>, 58% of Amazon\'s sales came from its millions of third-party sellers, many of whom ship directly to consumers. Many legitimate brands, including Doona, sell products through authorized third parties. However, items purchased this way may never be checked by Amazon employees or pass through an Amazon warehouse. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"A lot of people on the Amazon platform think that because it\'s on Amazon, it is a genuine product. And that\'s actually really not the case,\" said Raviv.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The product CNN bought was listed by a seller called Strolex and shipped from China. All US car seats are required to be certified according to NHTSA standards, but this seat did not have any US certification labels. On the Amazon listing, it claimed to have European certification, but when it arrived it was missing a required European certification label and the European registration number in the instruction manual was a copy of Doona\'s.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Fake and dangerous kids products are turning up for sale on Amazon','','publish','open','open','','fake-and-dangerous-kids-products-are-turning-up-for-sale-on-amazon','','','2019-12-24 03:10:25','2019-12-24 03:10:25','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=42',0,'post','',0),(43,1,'2019-12-24 03:09:35','2019-12-24 03:09:35','','191219171403-03-copycat-doona-crash-test-super-169','','inherit','open','closed','','191219171403-03-copycat-doona-crash-test-super-169','','','2019-12-24 03:09:35','2019-12-24 03:09:35','',42,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191219171403-03-copycat-doona-crash-test-super-169.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(44,1,'2019-12-24 03:10:22','2019-12-24 03:10:22','','191219170147-20191219-amazon-fake-products-doona-labels-super-tease','','inherit','open','closed','','191219170147-20191219-amazon-fake-products-doona-labels-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 03:10:22','2019-12-24 03:10:22','',42,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191219170147-20191219-amazon-fake-products-doona-labels-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(45,1,'2019-12-24 03:10:25','2019-12-24 03:10:25','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN Business) - </strong>The listing on Amazon (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=AMZN&amp;source=story_quote_link\">AMZN</a>) described it as a \"4 in 1 Baby car seat and Stroller\" and featured images of a popular brand called Doona, including a photo of the US President\'s daughter, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.pinterest.com/pin/449585975299565156/\" target=\"_blank\">Ivanka Trump, with hers</a>. Listed for $299, this copycat  was $200 cheaper than a real Doona. It was also potentially dangerous for children. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The car seat broke into pieces in a  30 mph crash test commissioned by CNN, failing to meet the basic standards set by US regulators. Video of the test shows the toddler dummy twisting as the car seat fractures and slides forward, with plastic pieces that have broken off it flying through the air. In an identical crash test scenario, an authentic Doona met federal requirements, with the car seat remaining in one piece and in place around the dummy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://thecarseatlady.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Dr. Alisa Baer</a>, a pediatrician and nationally certified child passenger safety instructor, reviewed the test results and said in a real crash such a car seat failure could put a child in \"grave danger,\" and lead to injuries to a child\'s chest, neck or head, including a traumatic brain injury. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CNN bought the copycat Doona and had it crash-tested at the University of Michigan Transportation Research Institute as part of a months-long investigation into the sale of counterfeit and patent-infringing children\'s products on Amazon. Seven different business owners told CNN their products were being actively targeted by counterfeiters using Amazon\'s marketplace for third-party vendors. The businesses said Amazon put the onus on them to report suspicious listings and that this often amounted to a game of \"whack-a-mole,\" in which new listings appeared almost as soon as flagged ones were taken down.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":43,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191219171403-03-copycat-doona-crash-test-super-169.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-43\"/><figcaption>A car seat purchased on Amazon fractured in a 30 mph crash test, failing to meet federal standards</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Under current US case law, Amazon is not liable when third-party products sold on its site directly infringe on intellectual property or have safety defects. The liability lies with the third-party seller. This is fundamentally different from how the law treats brick-and-mortar retailers like Target (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=TGT&amp;source=story_quote_link\">TGT</a>) or Walmart (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=WMT&amp;source=story_quote_link\">WMT</a>) or even your corner grocery. If you find a product at a physical store that infringes on your trademark, or you buy something defective there, you can sue the store even though they didn\'t make the product. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Counterfeits are a problem for many ecommerce platforms, not just Amazon, but Amazon is the world\'s largest ecommerce platform and its dominance is growing. According to <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.emarketer.com/content/us-ecommerce-2019\" target=\"_blank\">an estimate from data firm eMarketer</a>, Amazon controls 37.7% of US ecommerce sales and that share is expected to grow. Many of the brands that spoke to CNN told us they can\'t afford not to sell their products on Amazon. As an Amazon spokesperson said to CNN in a statement, \"our customers expect that when they make a purchase through Amazon\'s store—either directly from Amazon or from one of its millions of third-party sellers—they will receive authentic products.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amiad Raviv, the commercial manager of Doona, said the company has found more than 40 Amazon listings this year that contained fake versions of its products or versions that infringed on its intellectual property. Doona flags the listings they are concerned about to Amazon, which then removes them. According to Raviv and the other business owners CNN spoke with, this piecemeal process means listings are often online for several days, leading to a significant window when consumers can buy the potentially dangerous product. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The imitation Doonas are sold through Amazon\'s website or app, but not by Amazon directly. According to <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://ir.aboutamazon.com/static-files/0f9e36b1-7e1e-4b52-be17-145dc9d8b5ec\" target=\"_blank\">Amazon\'s 2018 annual report</a>, 58% of Amazon\'s sales came from its millions of third-party sellers, many of whom ship directly to consumers. Many legitimate brands, including Doona, sell products through authorized third parties. However, items purchased this way may never be checked by Amazon employees or pass through an Amazon warehouse. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"A lot of people on the Amazon platform think that because it\'s on Amazon, it is a genuine product. And that\'s actually really not the case,\" said Raviv.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The product CNN bought was listed by a seller called Strolex and shipped from China. All US car seats are required to be certified according to NHTSA standards, but this seat did not have any US certification labels. On the Amazon listing, it claimed to have European certification, but when it arrived it was missing a required European certification label and the European registration number in the instruction manual was a copy of Doona\'s.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Fake and dangerous kids products are turning up for sale on Amazon','','inherit','closed','closed','','42-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 03:10:25','2019-12-24 03:10:25','',42,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=45',0,'revision','',0),(46,1,'2019-12-24 03:13:46','2019-12-24 03:13:46','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN) - </strong>Boeing\'s Starliner <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/20/tech/boeing-starliner-launch-nasa-oft-scn-trnd/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">spacecraft</a> made a soft touch down in the desert of New Mexico early Sunday. It marked the end of a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/20/tech/boeing-starliner-launch-nasa-oft-scn-trnd/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">tense two-day effort</a> to return the vehicle to Earth after unexpected issues plagued its inaugural flight to orbit, forcing it to make an early return.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The spacecraft launched an uncrewed test flight on Friday but had to abort its mission to dock with the International Space Station when it failed to put itself on the right trajectory.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Starliner\'s return on Sunday was a win for Boeing because experts will be able to retrieve valuable data about whether the spacecraft, which is designed to fly NASA astronauts to the space station, can execute a safe landing after returning from orbit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing has worked for the past decade to prepare Starliner for crewed missions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NASA asked the private sector the design spacecraft capable of ferrying astronauts to the ISS after retiring the space shuttle program. NASA allotted Boeing $4.2 billion in 2014 for Starliner development and anticipated it would to be ready by 2017. But it\'s suffered numerous delays and development setbacks. SpaceX, which was allocated $2.6 billion, is also building a crew-worthy spacecraft and is years behind schedule.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The mission Starliner undertook this week was to be a massive milestone: It was expected to be the last major test before the craft was finally ready to fly NASA astronauts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Starliner successfully launched into space aboard a rocket Friday morning, but after detaching from the launch vehicle, it failed to put itself on the correct path to the space station.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Officials attributed the problem to an unsynchronized clock: A misread by Starliner\'s on-board systems put its timing system 11 hours off, Boeing executive Jim Chilton said Sunday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That triggered a ripple effect of other issues. It prevented the spacecraft from firing its engines at the right moment, which put it off course. And that caused the vehicle to lose connection with flight controllers on the ground for a crucial 8-minute period. Meanwhile, it burned through fuel it would have needed to comfortably correct course back toward the International Space Station.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ultimately, flight controllers determined that Starliner should not attempt to dock with the ISS, a feat that would require the spacecraft to maintain precise control as it approaches the massive orbiting laboratory while traveling more than 17,000 miles per hour.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With that option off the table, Boeing officials decided to put Starliner on a path back home so it could focus on proving the spacecraft can safely return to its landing site in New Mexico.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The spacecraft on Sunday guided itself back through the Earth\'s atmosphere, deployed parachutes and a halo of air bags, and made a gentle touchdown.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing officials said Sunday the spacecraft appeared to be in good health.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>What\'s next</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Make no mistake this did not go according to plan in every way that we would have hoped, but it\'s also true that we got a lot of really good information so we can keep making meaningful progress,\" NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine, who described the landing as an \"absolute bullseye,\" said Sunday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing and NASA will need to spend \"weeks or months\" reviewing data, Bridenstine said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That data will include information collected by an anthropomorphic test dummy, nicknamed <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/17/tech/rosie-test-dummy-boeing-starliner-trnd-scn/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Rosie</a> after the World War II icon Rosie the Riveter, which was strapped into Starliner and was equipped with dozens of sensors to measure the G-forces future astronauts may experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After thanking NASA for its support, Boeing\'s Chilton said he\'d \"like to express Boeing\'s regrets to the ISS crew to whom we did not bring the Christmas presents. Not cool.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Boeing\'s Starliner spacecraft makes safe landing after botched test flight','','publish','open','open','','boeings-starliner-spacecraft-makes-safe-landing-after-botched-test-flight','','','2019-12-24 03:13:46','2019-12-24 03:13:46','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=46',0,'post','',0),(47,1,'2019-12-24 03:13:22','2019-12-24 03:13:22','','191222085201-01-boeing-starliner-spacecraft-super-tease','','inherit','open','closed','','191222085201-01-boeing-starliner-spacecraft-super-tease','','','2019-12-24 03:13:22','2019-12-24 03:13:22','',46,'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/191222085201-01-boeing-starliner-spacecraft-super-tease.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(48,1,'2019-12-24 03:13:46','2019-12-24 03:13:46','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>New York (CNN) - </strong>Boeing\'s Starliner <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/20/tech/boeing-starliner-launch-nasa-oft-scn-trnd/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">spacecraft</a> made a soft touch down in the desert of New Mexico early Sunday. It marked the end of a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/20/tech/boeing-starliner-launch-nasa-oft-scn-trnd/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">tense two-day effort</a> to return the vehicle to Earth after unexpected issues plagued its inaugural flight to orbit, forcing it to make an early return.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The spacecraft launched an uncrewed test flight on Friday but had to abort its mission to dock with the International Space Station when it failed to put itself on the right trajectory.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Starliner\'s return on Sunday was a win for Boeing because experts will be able to retrieve valuable data about whether the spacecraft, which is designed to fly NASA astronauts to the space station, can execute a safe landing after returning from orbit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing has worked for the past decade to prepare Starliner for crewed missions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NASA asked the private sector the design spacecraft capable of ferrying astronauts to the ISS after retiring the space shuttle program. NASA allotted Boeing $4.2 billion in 2014 for Starliner development and anticipated it would to be ready by 2017. But it\'s suffered numerous delays and development setbacks. SpaceX, which was allocated $2.6 billion, is also building a crew-worthy spacecraft and is years behind schedule.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The mission Starliner undertook this week was to be a massive milestone: It was expected to be the last major test before the craft was finally ready to fly NASA astronauts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Starliner successfully launched into space aboard a rocket Friday morning, but after detaching from the launch vehicle, it failed to put itself on the correct path to the space station.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Officials attributed the problem to an unsynchronized clock: A misread by Starliner\'s on-board systems put its timing system 11 hours off, Boeing executive Jim Chilton said Sunday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That triggered a ripple effect of other issues. It prevented the spacecraft from firing its engines at the right moment, which put it off course. And that caused the vehicle to lose connection with flight controllers on the ground for a crucial 8-minute period. Meanwhile, it burned through fuel it would have needed to comfortably correct course back toward the International Space Station.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ultimately, flight controllers determined that Starliner should not attempt to dock with the ISS, a feat that would require the spacecraft to maintain precise control as it approaches the massive orbiting laboratory while traveling more than 17,000 miles per hour.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With that option off the table, Boeing officials decided to put Starliner on a path back home so it could focus on proving the spacecraft can safely return to its landing site in New Mexico.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The spacecraft on Sunday guided itself back through the Earth\'s atmosphere, deployed parachutes and a halo of air bags, and made a gentle touchdown.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing officials said Sunday the spacecraft appeared to be in good health.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>What\'s next</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Make no mistake this did not go according to plan in every way that we would have hoped, but it\'s also true that we got a lot of really good information so we can keep making meaningful progress,\" NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine, who described the landing as an \"absolute bullseye,\" said Sunday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Boeing and NASA will need to spend \"weeks or months\" reviewing data, Bridenstine said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That data will include information collected by an anthropomorphic test dummy, nicknamed <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2019/12/17/tech/rosie-test-dummy-boeing-starliner-trnd-scn/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Rosie</a> after the World War II icon Rosie the Riveter, which was strapped into Starliner and was equipped with dozens of sensors to measure the G-forces future astronauts may experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After thanking NASA for its support, Boeing\'s Chilton said he\'d \"like to express Boeing\'s regrets to the ISS crew to whom we did not bring the Christmas presents. Not cool.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Boeing\'s Starliner spacecraft makes safe landing after botched test flight','','inherit','closed','closed','','46-revision-v1','','','2019-12-24 03:13:46','2019-12-24 03:13:46','',46,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=48',0,'revision','',0),(49,1,'2019-12-24 03:16:05','2019-12-24 03:16:05','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Dublin, Ireland (CNN Business) - </strong>Artificially-generated faces of people who don\'t exist are being used to front fake Facebook (<a href=\"https://money.cnn.com/quote/quote.html?symb=FB&amp;source=story_quote_link\">FB</a>) accounts in an attempt to trick users and game the company\'s systems, the social media network said Friday. Experts who reviewed the accounts say it is the first time they have seen fake images like this being used at scale as part of a single social media campaign.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The accounts, which were removed by Facebook on Friday, were part of a network that generally posted in support of President Trump and against the Chinese government, experts who reviewed the accounts said. Many of the accounts promoted links to a Facebook page and website called \"The BL.\" Facebook said the accounts were tied to the US-based Epoch Media Group, which owns The Epoch Times newspaper, a paper tied to the Falun Gong movement that is similarly pro-Trump.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The publisher of the Epoch Times denied that Epoch and The BL were linked in emails to the fact-checking organization<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/12/13/facebook-bl-cib/\" target=\"_blank\"> Snopes earlier this year.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.theepochtimes.com/facebook-errs-in-connecting-epoch-media-group-to-bl_3180838.html\" target=\"_blank\">statement</a> released after this story initially published on Friday, Epoch Times publisher Stephen Gregory said, \"The Epoch Times and The BL media companies are unaffiliated. The BL was founded by a former employee, and employs some of our former employees. However, that some of our former employees work for BL is not evidence of any connection between the two organizations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"The BL is a publication of Epoch Times Vietnam. As can be seen in archived pages of The Epoch Times website, Epoch Times Vietnam was no longer listed as part of Epoch Media Group in October 2018.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In response, a Facebook spokesperson told CNN Business that executives at The BL were active administrators on Epoch Media Group Pages as recently as Friday morning.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The dystopian revelation of the use of artificially-generated images in this way points to an increasingly complicated online information landscape as America enters a presidential election year. Silicon Valley and the US intelligence community are still struggling with the fallout from widespread <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://money.cnn.com/2018/02/16/media/internet-research-agency-mueller-indictment/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">online interference in the 2016 presidential election.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Facebook accounts used profile pictures that appeared to show real people smiling and looking directly into a camera. But the people do not and have never existed, according to Facebook and other researchers. The images were created using artificial intelligence technology. The same basic methods are used to produce <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2019/01/business/pentagons-race-against-deepfakes/\" target=\"_blank\">deepfake videos</a> — fake videos that the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/26/tech/ai-deepfake-detection-2020/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">US intelligence community has warned</a> could be used as part of a foreign disinformation campaign targeting Americans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other fake accounts that were part of the same network used stolen pictures of real people, according to the social media investigations company Graphika and the thinktank the Atlantic Council. Facebook provided information to Graphika and the Atlantic Council for analysis in advance of Friday\'s announcement.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The accounts were used to run dozens of pro-Trump Facebook groups with names like \"America Needs President Trump,\" and \"WE STAND WITH TRUMP &amp; PENCE!,\" according to Graphika and the Atlantic Council.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The fact-checking organizations <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/12/13/facebook-bl-cib/\" target=\"_blank\">Snopes</a> and <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://analysis.leadstories.com/3471185-fake-faces-people-Who-Do-Not-Exist-Invade-Facebook-To-Influence-2020-Elections.html\" target=\"_blank\">Lead Stories</a> had reported in recent weeks and months about the use of artificial images on Facebook that were part of this network of accounts. <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/12/13/facebook-bl-cib/\" target=\"_blank\">Snopes published a story</a> last week criticizing Facebook\'s apparent inaction on the issue. Facebook said Friday it had \"benefited from open source reporting\" in the takedown but said that its own systems that monitor for coordinated and inauthentic behavior had proactively identified many of the accounts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<h3>Connection to Epoch Media Group</h3>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In all, Facebook said Friday, it had removed a network of 610 Facebook accounts, 89 pages, 90 groups, and 72 Instagram accounts. About 55 million accounts followed one or more of the pages, and the vast majority of followers were outside the United States, Facebook said. Facebook did not say if all of all these followers were real — some of them may themselves have been fake accounts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/epoch-times-begins-hiding-its-connection-huge-pro-trump-ad-n1045416\" target=\"_blank\">In August, Facebook banned ads</a> from The Epoch Times after an <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/trump-qanon-impending-judgment-day-behind-facebook-fueled-rise-epoch-n1044121\" target=\"_blank\">NBC News investigation</a> detailed how the newspaper was secretly running pro-Trump Facebook ads under alternate accounts. The Epoch Times\' publisher said in a statement to NBC News, \"The Epoch Times advertisements are print-subscription advertisements describing our paper\'s reporting — a popular practice of many publishers — and every one of these ads was approved by Facebook before publishing.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>-- CNN Business\' Rachel Metz contributed reporting.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Now fake Facebook accounts are using fake faces','','publish','open','open','','now-fake-facebook-accounts-are-using-fake-faces','','','2019-12-24 03:16:05','2019-12-24 03:16:05','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=49',0,'post','',0),(50,1,'2019-12-24 03:14:32','2019-12-24 03:14:32','','191113134925-facebook-platform---stock-super-t